04683nam a22006975i 9781400829545DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2008    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008295457 a10.1515/97814008295452doi  a(DE-B1597)528412  a(OCoLC)1058117823  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHC240 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a330.94a330.940551 aEichengreen, Barry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe European Economy since 1945 :bCoordinated Capitalism and Beyond /cBarry Eichengreen. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (520 p.) :b22 line illus. 39 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Princeton Economic History of the Western World ;v2300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF FIGURES -- tLIST OF TABLES -- tPREFACE -- tLIST OF ABBREVIATIONS -- tONE. Introduction -- tTWO. Mainsprings of Growth -- tTHREE. The Postwar Situation -- tFOUR. Dawn of the Golden Age -- tFIVE. Eastern Europe and the Planned Economy -- tSIX. The Integration of Western Europe -- tSEVEN. The Apex of the Golden Age -- tEIGHT. Mounting Payments Problems -- tNINE. Declining Growth, Rising Rigidities -- tTEN. The Collapse of Central Planning -- tELEVEN. Integration and Adjustment -- tTWELVE. Europe at the Turn of the Twenty-first Century -- tTHIRTEEN. The Future of the European Model -- tAPPENDIX. Sources of Growth -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1945, many Europeans still heated with coal, cooled their food with ice, and lacked indoor plumbing. Today, things could hardly be more different. Over the second half of the twentieth century, the average European's buying power tripled, while working hours fell by a third. The European Economy since 1945 is a broad, accessible, forthright account of the extraordinary development of Europe's economy since the end of World War II. Barry Eichengreen argues that the continent's history has been critical to its economic performance, and that it will continue to be so going forward. Challenging standard views that basic economic forces were behind postwar Europe's success, Eichengreen shows how Western Europe in particular inherited a set of institutions singularly well suited to the economic circumstances that reigned for almost three decades. Economic growth was facilitated by solidarity-centered trade unions, cohesive employers' associations, and growth-minded governments--all legacies of Europe's earlier history. For example, these institutions worked together to mobilize savings, finance investment, and stabilize wages. However, this inheritance of economic and social institutions that was the solution until around 1973--when Europe had to switch from growth based on brute-force investment and the acquisition of known technologies to growth based on increased efficiency and innovation--then became the problem. Thus, the key questions for the future are whether Europe and its constituent nations can now adapt their institutions to the needs of a globalized knowledge economy, and whether in doing so, the continent's distinctive history will be an obstacle or an asset.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400829545zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400829545.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA